    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Thursday Night</p>
      <p>Dearest Mate. What a charming letter from you today my Dear!-- With such a diagram!!-- Delicious!!--</p>
      <p>You are indeed kind about me. Mr Taylor says it is ulikely the Abscess will close for some time,-- many days at least;-- because it so very large &amp; so deep in. There is still an enormous inflamed callous,-- (like a huge egg), deep in up the vagina, &amp; all around the raw discharging orifice. But it is</p>
      <p>doing very well, &amp; so am I. In fact I am quite another being. Of course it is a sad nuisance to have a great sore under one,-- &amp; it is tender, &amp; crippling;-- but it seems like perfect case, compared with the past.--</p>
      <p>Mr Taylor seems to wonder that I take it all so quietly, &amp; am so little rendered helpless by it. He says most people would be in bed, &amp; not move hand</p>
      <p>or foot;-- instead of which he finds me usually dressed, &amp; always ready to hobble about for my own little wants when possible.--</p>
      <p>In fact he would scarcely have thought it possible, had he not seen it.</p>
      <p>He said this evening, "Upon my word Ma'am, "if this can't keep you "quiet, I don't know what "can; for a more painful "disabling thing than you "have had, I know not; &amp; "it is still in a most sad "state as far as its crippling</p>
      <p>"effects go. But you take it "all just like nothing. Now "Ma'am do keep still".--</p>
      <p>Pray reply for me to the enclosed from Mrs Carpenter, without delay.</p>
      <p>They do not know of my having been here at all;-- &amp; still less of my incapacities from the Abscess. Pray explain all this for me, &amp; mind I say that but for this I should have acknowledged the receipt of Dr C's packet.--</p>
      <p>No-- I have altered my mind; &amp; enclose you a</p>
      <p>2) little pencil note of mine for Mrs C--, to which you must add a note, as you will see.--</p>
      <p>I imagine I am now, for a time, in statu quo;-- but it is everything to be out of pain &amp; easy.--</p>
      <p>I am nothing short of enchanted with the surveying Mount.</p>
      <p>Late at Night. I have a report to give you from Mr Taylor, who has been to examine the Abscess thoroughly after my</p>
      <p>Bath.--</p>
      <p>It is this: that it is of such vast extent, &amp; the inflammation &amp; induration are so intense all around, that it must take a long time before the discharge can subside. In another week he may be able to give some opinion on the subject.</p>
      <p>I had much under-stated the size to you yesterday. It is enormous. The wound is today a Crown-piece in size also.--</p>
      <p>But it is all healthy, &amp; quite favorable. I suffer little</p>
      <p>3) Friday Morg.</p>
      <p>A glorious enchanting day! Tho' I can profit not, in any active way, yet the very aspect is delicious.--</p>
      <p>From the opinion delivered last night, you will see that time &amp; patience must be looked to. The gathering (so far from being completed) seems merely beginning.-- I am quite content, happy &amp; comfortable;-- for I have the best attendance, (medical &amp; personal), &amp; every real comfort. I am also more thankful than I can say for 2 things,-- the first</p>
      <p>that there has been no operation necessary. Mr Taylor had yesterday to cut thro' an inch or two of flesh in another case of a lady, to get at an Abscess in her side!--</p>
      <p>The 2nd is, that there is no real call for me at home or elsewhere;-- but that all is well everywhere. I am utterly immoveable of course; while it remains open. Besides that, I could not leave my advice.--</p>
      <p>I feel to be a most &amp; harmless Bird;-- &amp; only fear your getting to think me useless lumber &amp; a sad bore.-- But you are a dear good Crow.</p>
      <p>Mr Taylor says it is of great consequence that my mind &amp; feelings should be at ease, &amp; that I should have no anxiety as to being elsewhere. He was relieved when I assured him I had not;-- &amp; that you understood the nature of the case;-- &amp; also that fortunately there was nothing at present to press my being at home; for that in fact I had intended being away this ensuing few weeks, with the exception of perhaps one week or a few days.--</p>
      <p>You (via Thomas) will hear tomorrow by parcel. I</p>
      <p>always look forward to letters from you, my Dear. They do so amuse me.--</p>
      <p>The Poor Prisoner</p>
    </div></body>
